(41, 11, 10, 23, 9, 6, 7, 'kingdom of our father David', 'Connection of David''s Kingdom', 'Both passages emphasize the kingdom of David and its significance. Mark 11:10 references the kingdom of David, while Isaiah 9:6-7 speaks of a ruler on David''s throne, linking the two texts thematically.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 11, 11, 43, 8, 1, 2, 'into the temple', 'Jesus'' Movement to the Temple', 'This connection highlights Jesus'' movement between locations, specifically his return to the temple. Both passages depict Jesus entering the temple, emphasizing his active role in teaching and engaging with the people.', 'parallel', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 11, 11, 26, 8, 9, 9, 'looked round about upon all things', 'Jesus'' Observation of Abominations', 'This connection highlights Jesus'' observation of the temple in Mark 11:11 and the call to witness wickedness in Ezekiel 8:9. Both passages emphasize the significance of recognizing wrongdoing within sacred spaces.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 11, 11, 36, 1, 12, 12, 'looked round about upon all things', 'Judgment in Jerusalem', 'This connection highlights the theme of Jesus examining Jerusalem, paralleling Zephaniah''s imagery of searching Jerusalem. Both passages emphasize a divine scrutiny of the city and its inhabitants.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 11, 11, 39, 3, 1, 1, NULL, 'Connection of Jesus and the Temple', 'Both passages emphasize the significance of the temple. In Mark, Jesus enters the temple, while Malachi speaks of the Lord coming to his temple, highlighting a prophetic fulfillment.', 'prophecy', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 11, 11, 40, 21, 10, 17, NULL, 'Jesus'' Actions in the Temple', 'Both passages emphasize Jesus entering the temple and interacting with its activities. Mark notes his observation before leaving, while Matthew details his actions of cleansing the temple and healing. This connection highlights the significance of Jesus'' authority in the temple.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 11, 11, 42, 19, 41, 45, 'into the temple', 'Jesus'' Entry and Temple Actions', 'Both passages emphasize Jesus'' actions in Jerusalem, particularly his visit to the temple. Mark describes Jesus looking around the temple, while Luke highlights his emotional response and subsequent actions within the temple.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 11, 11, 42, 21, 37, 38, 'he went out unto Bethany', 'Jesus'' Movement in Jerusalem', 'Both passages emphasize Jesus'' presence in the temple during the day and his departure at night. Mark notes his evening exit to Bethany, while Luke describes his nightly stay on the mount of Olives.', 'parallel', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 11, 12, 40, 21, 18, 22, 'he was hungry', 'Connection of Jesus'' Hunger', 'Both passages emphasize Jesus'' hunger as a catalyst for his actions. In Mark, his hunger leads to the encounter with the fig tree, which is further elaborated in Matthew, where the tree''s lack of fruit symbolizes a deeper lesson about faith.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 11, 12, 40, 4, 2, 2, 'he was hungry', 'Connection of Hunger in Scripture', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of hunger experienced by Jesus. In Mark, he is hungry after leaving Bethany, while in Matthew, he is hungry after fasting for forty days.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 11, 12, 43, 19, 28, 28, NULL, 'Connection of Thirst and Hunger', 'This connection highlights the physical needs of Jesus, as both passages mention his thirst and hunger. The mention of hunger in Mark 11:12 and thirst in John 19:28 emphasizes the human experience of Jesus.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 11, 12, 42, 4, 2, 2, 'he was hungry', 'Connection of Hunger in Scripture', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of hunger experienced by Jesus. In Mark, he is hungry after leaving Bethany, while in Luke, he hungers after fasting for forty days.', 'theme', 0.307, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 11, 12, 43, 4, 6, 7, 'he was hungry', 'Jesus'' Physical Needs', 'This connection highlights Jesus'' physical needs, as both passages depict Him in a state of need: hungry in Mark and weary and asking for water in John. Both instances illustrate His humanity and reliance on others.', 'theme', 0.307, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 11, 12, 58, 2, 17, 17, 'he was hungry', 'Human Experience and Christ''s Nature', 'This connection highlights the humanity of Christ, as seen in his hunger in Mark 11:12, which reflects his identification with human experiences. Hebrews 2:17 emphasizes that he was made like his brethren, reinforcing the theme of Christ''s shared human condition.', 'theme', 0.307, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 11, 13, 40, 21, 19, 19, 'found nothing but leaves', 'Fig Tree Withering Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the fig tree found with leaves but no fruit. This connection highlights the consequence of barrenness, as seen in Matthew''s account of the tree withering. The similar imagery of the fig tree serves to link the two narratives.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 11, 13, 42, 13, 6, 9, NULL, 'Fig Tree Symbolism in Scripture', 'Both passages emphasize the lack of fruit on the fig tree, illustrating themes of expectation and disappointment. The fig tree serves as a metaphor for spiritual barrenness and the need for cultivation to produce fruit.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 11, 13, 23, 5, 7, 7, 'found nothing but leaves', 'Judgment and Fruitlessness Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of expectation versus reality. In both passages, there is an anticipation of fruitful outcomes—figs in Mark and judgment in Isaiah—but instead, both reveal disappointment and lack of fulfillment.', 'theme', 0.307, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
